stickerText: My English Pronouns are they/them and she/hers.
What are yours?

It’s International 
Pronouns Day,
and I want to share what today personally means.
Today is mean to highlight the diversity of pronouns
and their importance.
Within the English language, pronouns indicate and
convey someone’s personhood, and they affirm
how they understand themselves in this world.
To purposefully ignore someone’s pronouns or to
use the incorrect pronouns, is a form of violence.
It shows that you don’t really respect who they are,
or care enough about them.
Today, learn a little bit more about the importance of
pronouns, and ask yourself, which ones do you use.
Thank you.

stickerText: ✨ stitch incoming ✨

Yes…and no. 
And, lemme tell you why.

So there’s a document from like the 60s*, that talks about that the intention of 
higher education

*correction: 40s and it’s  
American Council on Education. (1949). The student personnel point of view
is to reinforce / expand American democracy.
Um…aka settler colonialism
I mean…makes sense, considering in the 16th century, colleges changed
Ex: Harvard changed their charters in 1650.
*correction: 17th century.

their charters, so that 
they can “educate” 
Indigenous Peoples.
“Educate.”

Then throughout the 1800s, you have the 
Morrill Land Grant Act,
which basically stole land from Native / Indigenous Peoples
and then funded public universities with specialities in agriculture and military tactics.
(yeah…)
So, arguably, higher education, based on those two examples, was created for Indigenous Peoples.
But that creation is rooted in genocide.
Higher Education & Genocide

stickerText: Online dating can be confusing and scary. I know for me, as a Native person, it has been.
Yet, StrongHearts Native Helpline, a 24/7, safe, anonymous, confidential

domestic, dating and sexual violence helpline for American Indians and 
Alaska Natives, has

articles and resources that make navigating the world of online dating just 
a little bit easier.

For example, here are 
5 Red Flags of Online Dating 
that I found out.
1. A vague or incomplete profile
Now…obviously this can be up for interpretation, yet in my experience it has been an indication of catfishing.
It is important to get to know the person, and not necessarily the profile.
Remember that.
2. Sexually-explicit messages right away

Everyone uses dating apps differently, I recognize that.
Yet if someone sends you a sexually-explicit message without your consent,
then that is a BIG RED FLAG, and please proceed with caution.
That is a sign that they do not respect your boundaries.

3. Irritated with Lack of Haste in Response or
Over-Messaging.
I will be the first to admit that I do not respond to messages in a timely manner. That is my fault.
BUT if someone uses small forms of guilt and manipulation to get a response out of you, then that is a BIG red flag.
It means that they do not respect your time and, again, boundaries.
4. Lack of Respect for Digital Boundaries
Now, this might not be quite as obvious, yet if someone you matched with suggests moving off the dating app,
trying to follow, or friend you, and you are uncomfortable with that, then they need to respect your decision.
5. “Don’t swipe right if you…”
Personally, this prompt is amusing, and can be a funny ice breaker.
Yet, it could also be a red flag. For example, if someone says:
“don’t swipe right if you don’t smudge everyday”
or “don’t swipe right if you don’t wake up before the sun and go on a run.”
Both of these examples can indicate someone who feels superior when it comes to spirituality and culture.
The start of any healthy relationship should not begin with hard-to-reach expectations.
For more insightful articles and resources, especially ones that are culturally relevant to you,

visit: strongheartshelpline.org 
and follow them @strongheartsdv
Thank you.

5 Red Flags of 
Online Dating

stickerText: Please go watch that video
because I think this a great entry point for understanding
some aspects of decolonization, particularly within the US empire.
You see, many colonizers just did not have the cognitive capacity to fully
comprehend the ways of being and knowing that were unique to many Indigenous Peoples.
And so, when we demand the return of Indigenous land and life (Tuck & Yang, 2012),
we are demanding that these systems of exploitation and violence be dismantled -
systems of capitalism, systems of yt supremacy, systems of colonization,
systems of anything that is particularly violent and colonial.
Thus, the work of decolonization within the US Empire must center the
experiences and ways of knowing of Indigenous Peoples.

Return of Indigenous Land & Life

stickerText: Hey…I have something wonderful to share with y’all. Give me a moment...

It’s this beautiful new book called FireKeeper’s Daughter by Angeline Boulley, who is a member of the Sault Ste. Marie Tribe of

INDIGENOUS

especially through Daunis Fontaine and how we live and earn our truths.
If you’re interested, visit FirekeepersDaugther.com to start reading.

stickerText:
From the 1800s-1950s, 
Native American children were stolen from their homes.
They were forced to attend American Indian Boarding Schools.
At these schools, many of them were abused.
They were trying to beat the culture out of us.
Until we became like them.
But no more.
Today, we will celebrate and fight for our language and culture.
